---
import ArticleLayout from '../layouts/ArticleLayout.astro';
import Reassurance from '../components/Reassurance.astro';
import MidCta from '../components/MidCta.astro';
import PullQuote from '../components/PullQuote.astro';
import FaqSection from '../components/FaqSection.astro';
import CtaBlock from '../components/CtaBlock.astro';
import EnquiryForm from '../components/locked/EnquiryForm.astro';
import RelatedPanel from '../components/RelatedPanel.astro';
import site from '../config/site';

const reassuranceLines = [
  'Paid in US dollars or euros under contract.',
  'Income covered by the Seafarers Earnings Deduction.',
  'Rotational work with months at sea.',
  'Limited recent UK address history.',
];

const faqs = [
  {
    q: "Can I get a mortgage if I'm paid in dollars or euros?",
    a: 'Yes. Many lenders accept foreign currency income, though most apply a discount to allow for exchange rate movement. The size of that discount varies by lender, so choosing the right lender can change what you are able to borrow.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Does the Seafarers Earnings Deduction stop me getting a mortgage?',
    a: 'No. The Seafarers Earnings Deduction reduces your UK tax to nil when you qualify, and lenders who understand seafarers assess your gross contracted income rather than your tax return. The obstacle is only ever lender choice, not the deduction itself.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Can I get a mortgage with months at sea and gaps in my UK address history?',
    a: 'Yes. Rotational work and limited recent UK address history are normal for seafarers, and the right lenders are used to seeing them. We match your circumstances to a lender whose criteria fit how you live and work.',
  },
  {
    q: 'How do I start?',
    a: 'Use the 60-second check and a Mortgage One adviser will review your answers and tell you where you stand. You can also call us on 01202 155992. You must be on UK soil to receive advice.',
  },
];

const relatedCards = [
  { title: 'Foreign currency income', href: '/seafarer-mortgage-foreign-currency-income', line: 'How lenders convert and discount non-sterling pay.' },
  { title: 'Seafarers Earnings Deduction mortgages', href: '/seafarers-earnings-deduction-mortgage', line: 'Getting a mortgage while you claim the deduction.' },
  { title: 'Merchant navy mortgages', href: '/merchant-navy-mortgage', line: 'Specialist help for merchant navy pay.' },
  { title: 'Seafarer mortgage services', href: `${site.www}/seafarers`, line: 'How Mortgage One arranges seafarer cases.' },
  { title: 'Expat mortgages', href: `${site.www}/expats`, line: 'Mortgages for UK nationals living abroad.' },
  { title: 'Check your eligibility', href: '/check', line: 'Five quick questions, about 60 seconds.' },
];
---

<ArticleLayout
  title="Can I Get a Mortgage as a Seafarer? | Mortgage One"
  description="Yes, seafarers can get a UK mortgage. How lenders view foreign currency pay, the Seafarers Earnings Deduction and time at sea, from Mortgage One."
  eyebrow="Seafarer mortgage questions"
  heading="Can I get a mortgage as a seafarer?"
  breadcrumbs={[
    { name: 'Home', href: '/' },
    { name: 'Can I get a mortgage as a seafarer?', href: '/mortgage-as-a-seafarer' },
  ]}
  scenario="seafarer"
>
  <p>
    Yes, seafarers can and do get UK mortgages. Whether you can comes down to how your income is evidenced and finding a lender that fits how you are paid. If you have been declined by a high street bank, that tells you very little about what the rest of the market will say.
  </p>

  <Reassurance title="Situations we see regularly" lines={reassuranceLines} />

  <h2>Why do seafarers get turned down by high street lenders?</h2>
  <p>
    High street affordability checks are automated and built around PAYE payslips and a steady UK footprint. Contract
    pay, foreign currency and a nil tax bill can each trip an automated decline, even where the underlying income is
    strong and stable.
  </p>
  <p>
    A decline from one lender is a criteria mismatch, not a verdict. It tells you that one set of rules did not fit your
    circumstances, and almost nothing about what the rest of the market will say.
  </p>

  <MidCta
    text="Tell us how you're paid and we'll tell you where you stand."
    label="Start the 60-Second Check"
    scenario="seafarer"
    src="/mortgage-as-a-seafarer"
  />

  <h2>What about foreign currency income?</h2>
  <p>
    Many lenders apply a discount to non-sterling income to allow for exchange rate movement, and the size of that
    discount varies by lender, so the lender choice can change what you can borrow more than the rate does. We go
    through how lenders convert and reduce it on our
    <a href="/seafarer-mortgage-foreign-currency-income">foreign currency income</a> page.
  </p>

  <h2>Does the Seafarers Earnings Deduction cause problems?</h2>
  <p>
    The Seafarers Earnings Deduction (SED) legitimately reduces UK tax to nil for qualifying seafarers, and some lenders
    misread a nil tax return as nil income. Lenders familiar with seafarers assess gross contracted income instead. Our
    <a href="/seafarers-earnings-deduction-mortgage">Seafarers Earnings Deduction</a> page covers the evidence a lender
    will want.
  </p>

  <PullQuote quote="A declined application from one lender says almost nothing about what the rest of the market will say." />

  <h2>How much deposit do I need?</h2>
  <p>
    There is no single figure. It depends on residency, how you are paid and the property itself. Non-resident cases
    often need a larger deposit, while UK-resident seafarers can frequently access standard deposit levels, subject to
    criteria.
  </p>

  <MidCta
    text="Paid in dollars, on rotation, claiming SED? Each of those changes which lenders work for you. Run the 60-second check and see your realistic options."
    scenario="seafarer"
    src="/mortgage-as-a-seafarer"
  />

  <h2>Do I need a specialist broker?</h2>
  <p>
    Seafarer income is not unusual, but it is read very differently from one lender to the next, and a broker who places
    these cases regularly knows where to take yours. Mortgage One has access to plans from the whole of market and
    arranges seafarer cases as a core part of the business, not an exception to it. Merchant navy crews, who often
    combine foreign currency, rotation and the deduction at once, have a dedicated
    <a href="/merchant-navy-mortgage">merchant navy mortgages</a> guide.
  </p>
  <p>You must be on UK soil to receive advice.</p>

  <h2>The four questions every lender asks</h2>
  <p>
    When a lender weighs a seafarer case, it works through four questions in turn. Is the borrowing affordable once your
    assessed income is set against your commitments. Is the income itself acceptable under that lender's policy, whatever
    currency it arrives in. Does your credit history fit the rules. And can the whole picture be evidenced cleanly. Answer
    yes to all four and the case proceeds like any other residential application. A high street decline almost always
    means a no on the second question, the income, because an automated system could not read seafarer pay, rather than
    because the borrowing was unaffordable.
  </p>
  <p>
    Specialist lenders take a more considered view of each one. On affordability, many work to income multiples of around
    4.5 times your assessed income, and some stretch to 5 times for higher earners or certain professionals, always
    subject to their own stress testing. On the income question, a lender that knows the sector is comfortable with
    contract pay, a rotational pattern and the Seafarers Earnings Deduction sitting behind a low tax bill. On credit, the
    test is the same as it is for any borrower. On evidence, the lender will want an employment contract showing your
    rotation, three to six months of payslips or remittance advices, bank statements showing the credits arriving, a
    sea-service letter, and proof of your UK address and deposit.
  </p>

  <h2>How specialist lenders weigh seafarer income</h2>
  <p>
    Deposit and loan to value sit inside the affordability and policy questions rather than beside them. A UK-resident
    seafarer paid in sterling can often access standard high-street loan to value levels, so the deposit looks like any
    other residential case. Where part or all of your income arrives in a foreign currency, or you are not UK resident,
    lenders tend to ask for more, frequently 15% to 25% or more, and some of those cases are best placed with expat or
    international lenders. None of that changes the four questions. It changes which lender answers them in your favour,
    which is the whole job of matching the case to the market.
  </p>
  <p>
    This is why two lenders can look at the same seafarer and reach different borrowing figures. One may accept the income
    in full and ask for a modest deposit, while another discounts the same pay and wants more down. Neither is wrong under
    its own rules. The difference is policy, and policy is something a whole-of-market broker can search before you apply
    rather than after a decline. We line your four answers up against the lenders most likely to say yes to all of them at
    once.
  </p>
  <p>
    It is worth being clear about what none of the four questions ask. None of them asks whether you work at sea, how long
    your tours are, or whether your tax bill is low because of the Seafarers Earnings Deduction. Those are facts about how
    you earn, not strikes against you. A lender that has placed seafarers before treats a settled rotation, a foreign
    currency salary and a nil tax position as ordinary features of the work, and tests them through the same four
    questions it would apply to anyone. The decline you may have had from a high street bank was an automated system
    failing to ask those questions properly, not the market's verdict on your income.
  </p>

  <h2>A worked example for a seafarer mortgage</h2>
  <p>
    Take a merchant navy officer earning £52,000, paid in sterling, UK resident, on a settled six weeks on, six weeks off
    rotation, with a 15% deposit saved and a standard residential purchase in mind. Run the four questions across the
    case. The income is sterling and contracted, so it is acceptable. The rotation reads as stable employment rather than
    a gap. The credit history is clean, and the deposit and UK address can both be evidenced. A lender working at around
    4.5 times the assessed income would look at borrowing of roughly £234,000, subject to its affordability test.
  </p>
  <p>
    Because the pay is in sterling and the borrower is UK resident, this case sits close to a standard high-street profile
    rather than a specialist one, and the deposit behaves the same way it would for any residential applicant. The
    rotation and the job title do not, on their own, hold it back. Once the income is read for what it is, the borrowing
    follows the same arithmetic as any other residential mortgage.
  </p>
  <p>
    Change one detail and the case moves towards specialist territory, but the framework does not change. Pay part of that
    £52,000 in dollars and a discount enters the income question. Add a spell of non-residence and the deposit question
    tightens. The four questions still decide it, and a lender that knows seafarers still answers them. That is why the
    same approach works whether your case looks like this example or carries several complications at once.
  </p>
  <p>
    Figures are illustrative. Your actual borrowing depends on your full circumstances, the lender and an affordability
    assessment.
  </p>

  <FaqSection items={faqs} />

  <CtaBlock
    heading="Find out where you stand"
    line="Tell us how you are paid and a Mortgage One adviser will review your answers."
    label="Check Your Eligibility"
    scenario="seafarer"
    src="/mortgage-as-a-seafarer"
  />

  <EnquiryForm scenario="seafarer" />

  <RelatedPanel cards={relatedCards} />

  <p class="risk-warning">
    Think carefully before securing your debts against your home. Your home may be repossessed if you do not keep up
    repayments on your mortgage.
  </p>
</ArticleLayout>

